|[[2017 Badminton Asia Championships|2017 Wuhan]]}} | {{Nowrap|Women's singles}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Badminton Asia Championships#Badminton Asia Mixed Team Championships|Asia Mixed Team Championships]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2017 Badminton Asia Mixed Team Championships|2017 Ho Chi Minh]] | Mixed team }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Badminton Asia Championships#Badminton Asia Team Championships|Asia Team Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2016 Badminton Asia Team Championships|2016 Hyderabad]] | Women's team }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2018 Badminton Asia Team Championships|2018 Alor Setar]] | Women's team }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Youth Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[Badminton at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics|2014 Nanjing]] | [[Badminton at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics \u2013 Girls' singles|Girls' singles]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[BWF World Junior Championships|World Junior Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2014 BWF World Junior Championships|2014 Alor Setar]] | [[2014 BWF World Junior Championships \u2013 Teams event|Mixed team]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2015 BWF World Junior Championships|2015 Lima]] | [[2015 BWF World Junior Championships \u2013 Teams event|Mixed team]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[2014 BWF World Junior Championships|2014 Alor Setar]] | [[2014 BWF World Junior Championships \u2013 Girls singles|Girls' singles]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2013 BWF World Junior Championships|2013 Bangkok]] | [[2013 BWF World Junior Championships \u2013 Girls singles|Girls' singles]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2013 BWF World Junior Championships|2013 Bangkok]] | [[2013 BWF World Junior Championships \u2013 Teams event|Mixed team]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Asian Junior Badminton Championships|Asian Junior Championships]] }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2013 Asian Junior Badminton Championships|2013 Kota Kinabalu]] | Mixed team }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2014 Asian Junior Badminton Championships|2014 Taipei]] | Mixed team }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2015 Badminton Asia Junior Championships|2015 Bangkok]] | Girls' singles }}\n{{MedalGold | [[2015 Badminton Asia Junior Championships|2015 Bangkok]] | Mixed team }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[2013 Asian Junior Badminton Championships|2013 Kota Kinabalu]] | Girls' singles }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{flagicon|International Olympic Committee}} [[Mixed-NOCs]] }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Youth Olympic Games]] }}\n{{MedalBronze | [[Badminton at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics|2014 Nanjing]] | [[Badminton at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics \u2013 Mixed doubles|Mixed doubles]] }}\n| bwf_id                  = 4C24F628-477B-4A65-B2E0-67342034035E\n}}\n\n'''He Bingjiao''' ({{zh|s=\u4f55\u51b0\u5a07|p=H\u00e9 B\u012bngji\u0101o}}; Mandarin pronunciation: {{IPAc-cmn|h|e|2|-|b|ing|1|.|j|iao|1|}}; born 21 March 1997) is a Chinese [[badminton]] player. She began to receive intensive badminton training at the Suzhou Junior Sports School, when she was only 7 years old. Five years later, she was sent to study in Nanjing and for tougher training there. The junior already competed in the senior level, and made her first senior international debut at the [[2013 Vietnam Open Grand Prix|2013 Vietnam Open]]. In 2014 she competed at the [[Badminton at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics|Summer Youth Olympics]], winning a gold medal in the girls' singles and a bronze in the mixed doubles event.<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web |title=Players: He Bingjiao |url=http://bwfbadminton.com/player/87434/he-bingjiao |publisher=[[Badminton World Federation]] |accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=16-year-old Upsets World No 1 to Take Badminton Gold at Youth Olympics |url=http://www.womenofchina.cn/womenofchina/html1/people/sportswomen/17/5453-1.htm |publisher=[[All-China Women's Federation|Women of China]] |accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== 2013 ===\nHe Bingjiao started playing at international tournaments when she was 16 years of age. She reached semi finals of [[2013 Asian Junior Badminton Championships|Asian Junior Championships]] where she was beaten by Thai [[Busanan Ongbamrungphan]] in 2 straight games. She also reached the semi finals of [[2013 BWF World Junior Championships|World Junior Championships]] and faced defeat by Japanese [[Aya Ohori]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Early celebrations for China and Japan\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2013/11/03/scg-bwf-world-junior-championships-2013-early-celebrations-for-china-and-japan/}}</ref>\n\nShe thereafter reached semi finals of [[2013 Korea Open Grand Prix Gold|Korea Grand Prix Gold]] tournament and went losing to [[Bae Yeon-ju]]. She contested in her first Superseries Premier tournament at [[2013 China Open Super Series Premier|China Open]], where she was defeated by [[Li Xuerui]] in the second round. She won [[2013 Vietnam Open Grand Prix|Vietnam Open]] defeating Indonesian [[Hera Desi]] in just 21 minutes.\n\n=== 2014 ===\nAt the [[2014 BWF World Junior Championships|2014  World Junior Championships]], she avenged her defeat to [[Aya Ohori]] in World Junior Championships last year, beating her in 2 straight games. However she has to settle for silver medal after she lost to [[Akane Yamaguchi]] in a tightly contested final match of 3 games 21\u201314, 18\u201321, 13\u201321.<ref>{{cite web|title=Akane Yamaguchi beats He Bingjiao\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2014/04/18/bwf-world-junior-championships-2014-day-6-chen-stars-for-china/}}</ref> Her biggest victory came at [[Badminton at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics|Youth Olympic Games]], where she defeated Akane Yamaguchi in yet another difficult match and took revenge of her defeat in World Junior Championships final.<ref>{{cite web|title=He Bingjiao battles past Yamaguchi\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2014/08/22/youth-olympic-games-2014-day-6-he-bing-jiao-battles-past-yamaguchi/}}</ref> She also had good campaign at the [[2014 Bitburger Open Grand Prix Gold|Bitburger Open]], where she defeated prominent opponents like [[Michelle Li (badminton)|Michelle Li]] and [[Zhang Beiwen]], but finished as runner-up after her defeat against [[Sun Yu (badminton)|Sun Yu]].\n\n=== 2015 ===\nShe won first title of the year at [[2015 China Masters Grand Prix Gold|China Masters]], defeating [[Hui Xirui]] for the title.<ref>{{cite web|title=He Bingjiao, Wang Zhengming emerge victorious\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2015/04/20/wang-zhengming-he-bingjiao-emerge-champions-bonny-china-masters-2015-review/}}</ref> She also got a final spot in [[2015 New Zealand Open Grand Prix Gold|New Zealand Open]], but was defeated by Japanese player [[Saena Kawakami]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Saena kawakami springs a surprise\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2015/05/04/saena-kawakami-springs-a-surprise-skycity-new-zealand-open-2015-review/}}</ref> \nShe suffered a shocking defeat in the quarter finals in [[2015 BWF World Junior Championships|World Junior Championships]] by [[Natsuki Nidaira]] of Japan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Thai-tanic upset; Bingjiao beaten\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2015/11/13/thai-tanic-upset-bingjiao-beaten-day-4-yonex-bwf-world-junior-championships-2015/}}</ref> She was also defeated in the semi finals of [[2015 Macau Open Grand Prix Gold|Macau Open]] by [[Minatsu Mitani]]. \n\nShe claimed [[2015 Indonesian Masters Grand Prix Gold|Indonesian Masters]] title later this year; defeating [[Chen Yufei]] in the final. Her victories in the tournament included a biggest surprise against 2 time World Championship bronze medalist [[P. V. Sindhu]].\n\n=== 2016 ===\nAfter a disappointing start in the year, she performed well at the [[2016 All England Super Series Premier|All England Open]], where she was defeated in the second round by her teammate [[Wang Yihan]] in a tough 2 game match. She had one of the greatest tournaments of her career at the [[2016 Swiss Open Grand Prix Gold|Swiss Open]], where she defeated world's top players [[Ratchanok Intanon]], [[P. V. Sindhu]], [[Sun Yu (badminton)|Sun Yu]] to reach the finals. She defeated Wang Yihan in a one-sided final match and took revenge of her defeat in All England against her.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bingjiao comes of age\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2016/03/21/bingjiao-comes-of-age-finals-swiss-open-2016/}}</ref>\n\nShe also reached semi finals of Singapore Open<ref>{{cite web|title=Sun Yu beats Bingjiao\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2016/04/16/sony-days-here-again-day-5-oue-singapore-open-2016/}}</ref> and Chinese Taipei Open as well.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wang Shixian beats He Bingjiao\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2016/07/02/hosts-in-sight-of-three-titles-yonex-open-chinese-taipei-2016-day-4/}}</ref> She claimed her first Superseries title at the Japan Open, beating Sun Yu in the final.<ref>{{cite web|title=China's gen next delivers\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2016/09/25/chinas-gen-next-delivers-yonex-open-japan-2016-finals/}}</ref> She won French Open Superseries thereafter, defeating Zhang Beiwen in a very easy final 21\u20139, 21\u20139.<ref>{{cite web|title=He and Shi reign!\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2016/10/30/he-and-shi-reign-yonex-french-open-2016-singles-finals/}}</ref>\n\nShe defended her title successfully at the Bitburger Open, beating Nitchaon Jindapol in the final.<ref>{{cite web|title=China captures 4 titles at the Bitburger Open\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2016/11/07/china-capture-four-titles-bitburger-open-review/}}</ref> Due to her best performances, she also qualified for the season ending [[2016 BWF Super Series Finals|Superseries Finals]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Women Singles Qualifiers:Dubai World Superseries Finals 2016\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2016/12/06/womens-singles-qualifiers-dubai-world-superseries-finals/}}</ref> where she had satisfactory results, despite losing to [[Tai Tzu-ying]] and [[Sung Ji-hyun]], she won against Ratchanok Intanon after Intanon left the match trailing 19\u201321, 11\u201310 to He Bingjiao.\n\n=== 2017 ===\nShe started the year by reaching the second round at [[2017 All England Super Series Premier|All England Open]] where she nearly lost to Olympic Champion [[Carolina Mar\u00edn]] 21\u201315, 19\u201321, 10\u201321. She reached the semi finals of [[2017 Badminton Asia Championships|Asian Championships]] after a hard battle against Olympic silver medalist [[P. V. Sindhu]] in the quarter finals. But, she lost in the semi finals against [[Akane Yamaguchi]] in two straight games.<ref>{{cite web|title=Akane beats He Bingjiao\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2017/04/30/luhuang-on-a-roll-badminton-asia-championships-2017-day-5/}}</ref> \n\nShe was also the part of China's Sudirman Cup team that won the silver medal at that occasion after losing to South-Korea in the Final.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seoul Satisfying!\n|url=https://bwfsudirmancup.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2017/05/28/seoul-satisfying-final-total-bwf-sudirman-cup-2017/}}</ref> At the [[2017 BWF World Championships|World Championships]] in Glasgow, Scotland, she lost to [[Kirsty Gilmour]] in the third round in a thrilling match.<ref>{{cite web|title=Scottish Delight\n|url=https://bwfworldchampionships.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2017/08/25/chungkim-stay-in-hunt-day-4-total-bwf-world-championships-2017/}}</ref> She finished as semi-finalist at the Korean Open<ref>{{cite web|title=Sindhu beats He Bingjiao\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2017/09/16/all-indonesia-summit-clash-day-5-victor-korea-open-2016/}}</ref> and failed to defend her title in Japan after losing to Carolina Mar\u00edn in the final.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singles Finals:Daihatsu Yonex Japan Open\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2017/09/24/top-of-the-world-singles-finals-daihatsu-yonex-japan-open-2017/}}</ref>\n\nShe lost in the French Open also to Tai Tzu-ying in the semi finals, where also she aimed to defend her title.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tai beats He Bingjiao, sets up summit clash with Akane Yamaguchi\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2017/10/28/poliirahayu-stun-world-champs-day-5-yonex-french-open-2017/}}</ref> She qualified for the Dubai World Superseries Finals this time too,<ref>{{cite web|title=Last Shot for China's young guns\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2017/12/08/last-shot-for-chinas-young-guns/}}</ref> but lost all the group matches to P. V. Sindhu, Akane Yamaguchi and [[Sayaka Sato]] therefore denying her a semi finals spot.\n\n=== 2018 ===\nShe attained a semi final finish in Indonesia Masters after she got defeated by [[Tai Tzu-ying]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tai Tzu-ying triumph\n|url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2018/01/28/bright-day-for-hosts-day-5-daihatsu-indonesia-masters-2018/}}</ref> She beat [[Carolina Mar\u00edn]] for the first time in her career. She retired from the first round match in the [[All England Open]] against [[Goh Jin Wei]].\n\nShe reached the final of the Malaysia Open for the first time, but failed to give good fight to Tai Tzu-ying even after she had three game points in the first game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Four in a row for Tai\n|url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2018/07/01/lee-gets-his-dozen-finals-celcom-axiata-malaysia-open-2018/}}</ref> She also lost to Tai Tzu-ying in the semi finals of [[Indonesia Open (badminton)|Indonesia Open]] Super 1000 event.<ref>{{cite web|title=Fine display from Tai Tzu-ying\n|url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2018/07/07/back-in-the-mix-semi-finals-blibli-indonesia-open-2018/}}</ref>\n\nShe took biggest revenge against Tai Tzu-ying in World Championships, where she defeated her in the quarter finals in 3 games 21\u201318, 7\u201321, 21\u201313. With this win, she broke Tai Tzu-ying's 7 months unbeatable record which includes 35 straight wins.<ref>{{cite web|title=\"Top-Pled\"!\n|url=https://bwfworldchampionships.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2018/08/03/top-pled-day-5-total-bwf-world-championships-2018/}}</ref> She has to settle for a bronze medal after getting defeated by Carolina Mar\u00edn in yet another 3 game clash.<ref>{{cite web|title=History in the making\n|url=https://bwfworldchampionships.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2018/08/04/history-beckons-momota-pusarla-day-6-total-bwf-world-championships-2018/}}</ref>\n\nShe competed at the [[Badminton at the 2018 Asian Games|Asian Games]], where she lost to [[Nozomi Okuhara]] in round of 16. She has shown her great consistency after reaching semi finals of various other tournaments. She lost to Akane Yamaguchi in an epic clash at the semi finals of French Open. She was leading 22\u201320, 14\u20135, but Yamaguchi clawed back from that huge deficit and took victory finally 22\u201320, 19\u201321, 19\u201321.<ref>{{cite web|title=Yamaguchi beats He Bingjiao\n|url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2018/10/28/chen-stops-momota-semi-finals-yonex-french-open-2018/}}</ref> This was one of the long gruelling matches of her entire career. \n\nAlthough she qualified, she opted not to take part in first ever edition of [[2018 BWF World Tour Finals|World Tour Finals]] in her home country China; citing some injury problems she got during her match against [[Sung Ji-hyun]] in the Hongkong Open.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bingjiao retires, Sung Ji-hyun wins\n|url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2018/11/16/titans-shoot-down-kim-lee-day-4-yonex-sunrise-hong-kong-open-2018/}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019 ===\nShe reached semi finals of Indonesia Masters Super 500 tournament and lost to [[Saina Nehwal]] in their first ever clash 21\u201318, 12\u201321, 18\u201321.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nehwal get past He Bingjiao\n|url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2019/01/26/vintage-display-by-ahsan-setiawan-indonesia-masters/}}</ref> She lost in the quarter finals of All England Open to Akane Yamaguchi of Japan.<ref>{{cite web|title=He Bingjiao loses to Akane Yamaguchi\n|url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2019/03/08/sparkling-show-from-goh-lai-all-england-day-3/}}</ref> In India Open, she defeated defending champion [[Zhang Beiwen]] in the quarter finals and [[P. V. Sindhu]] for the fourth straight time in next round. but lost the final to [[Ratchanok Intanon]] in straight games. She lost to Intanon for first time ever.<ref>{{cite web|title=Intanon triumphs\n|url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2019/03/31/axelsen-intanon-are-champions-india-open-singles-finals/}}</ref>\n\nShe won silver medal at the Asian Championships following her defeat against Akane Yamaguchi again.<ref>{{cite web|title=Glory for Japan at the Badminton Asia Championships\n|url=https://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2019/04/29/glory-for-japan-at-badminton-asia-championships/}}</ref> After early losses in Indonesia, Japan and Thailand, she finished as quarter-finalists in the World Championships.\n\nShe got a title victory in Korea Open in 3 years after her last in 2016. She defeated Ratchanok Intanon even when she was 4 match points down.<ref>{{cite web|title=He Bingjiao pulls off an Escape act!\n|url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2019/09/29/bing-jiao-pulls-off-escape-act-korea-open-finals/}}</ref> \n\nShe had an upsetting campaign at the World Tour Finals, where she was defeated by [[Akane Yamaguchi]], [[Chen Yufei]] and [[P. V. Sindhu]]. She led against Sindhu in game one with huge 18\u20139 lead, but lost the match 19\u201321, 19\u201321.\n\n=== 2020 ===\nShe started her year with string of consistent performances; reaching the semi finals of Malaysia and Indonesia Masters. She lost to [[Pornpawee Chochuwong]] at the All England Open in round of 16.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chochuwong battles into quarters\n|url=https://bwfworldtour.bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2020/03/13/all-england-chochuwong-battles-into-quarters/}}</ref>\n\n== Achievements ==\n\n=== BWF World Championships ===\n''Women's singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Venue\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#F3E6D7\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2018 BWF World Championships \u2013 Women's singles|2018]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Nanjing Youth Olympic Sports Park]], [[Nanjing, China]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Carolina Mar\u00edn]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201313, 16\u201321, 13\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 3.png|Bronze]] '''Bronze'''\n|}\n\n=== Asian Championships ===\n''Women's singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Venue\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#ECF2FF\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2019 Badminton Asia Championships#Finals 2|2019]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Wuhan Gymnasium|Wuhan Sports Center Gymnasium]], [[Wuhan]], [[China]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Akane Yamaguchi]]\n| align=\"left\" | 19\u201321, 9\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 2.png|Silver]] '''Silver'''\n|- style=\"background:#ECF2FF\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2017 Badminton Asia Championships#Finals 2|2017]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Wuhan Gymnasium|Wuhan Sports Center Gymnasium]], [[Wuhan]], [[China]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Akane Yamaguchi]]\n| align=\"left\" | 15\u201321, 19\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 3.png|Bronze]] '''Bronze'''\n|}\n\n=== Youth Olympic Games ===\n''Girls' singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Venue\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#FBCEB1\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[Badminton at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics \u2013 Girls' singles|2014]]\n| align=\"left\" | Nanjing Sport Institute, [[Nanjing]], [[China]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Akane Yamaguchi]]\n| align=\"left\" | 22\u201324, 23\u201321, 21\u201317\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]] '''Gold'''\n|}\n\n''Mixed doubles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Venue\n! Partner\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#FBCEB1\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[Badminton at the 2014 Summer Youth Olympics \u2013 Mixed doubles|2014]]\n| align=\"left\" | Nanjing Sport Institute,<br>[[Nanjing]], [[China]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|SRI}} Sachin Angodavidanalage\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|THA}} Mek Narongrit <br /> {{flagicon|CHN}} Qin Jinjing\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201316, 21\u201318\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 3.png|Bronze]] '''Bronze'''\n|}\n\n=== BWF World Junior Championships ===\n''Girls' singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Venue\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#98FB98\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2014 BWF World Junior Championships \u2013 Girls singles|2014]]\n| align=\"left\" | Stadium Sultan Abdul Halim, [[Alor Setar]], [[Malaysia]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Akane Yamaguchi]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201314, 18\u201321, 13\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 2.png|Silver]] '''Silver'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#98FB98\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2013 BWF World Junior Championships \u2013 Girls singles|2013]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Hua Mark Indoor Stadium]], [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Aya Ohori]]\n| align=\"left\" | 16\u201321, 17\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 3.png|Bronze]] '''Bronze'''\n|}\n\n=== Asian Junior Championships ===\n''Girls' singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Venue\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#AABBCC\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2015 Badminton Asia Junior Championships \u2013 Girls' Singles|2015]]\n| align=\"left\" | CPB Badminton Training Center, [[Bangkok]], [[Thailand]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|THA}} [[Pornpawee Chochuwong]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201316, 21\u201317\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 1.png|Gold]] '''Gold'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#AABBCC\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2013 Asian Junior Badminton Championships \u2013 Girls singles|2013]]\n| align=\"left\" | Likas Indoor Stadium, [[Kota Kinabalu]], [[Malaysia]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|THA}} [[Busanan Ongbumrungpan]]\n| align=\"left\" | 16\u201321, 17\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | [[File:Med 3.png|Bronze]] '''Bronze'''\n|}\n\n=== BWF World Tour (1 title, 2 runners-up) ===\nThe BWF World Tour, announced on 19 March 2017 and implemented in 2018,<ref>{{cite news |title=BWF Launches New Events Structure |url=http://bwfbadminton.com/news-single/2017/03/19/bwf-launches-new-event-structure/ |publisher=[[Badminton World Federation]] |date=29 November 2017}}</ref> is a series of elite badminton tournaments, sanctioned by [[Badminton World Federation]] (BWF). The BWF World Tour are divided into six levels, namely World Tour Finals, Super 1000, Super 750, Super 500, Super 300 (part of the HSBC World Tour), and the BWF Tour Super 100.<ref>{{cite news |title=Action-Packed Season Ahead! |url=http://bwfworldtour.com/news-single/2018/01/10/action-packed-season-ahead/ |publisher=[[Badminton World Federation]] |date=15 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n''Women's singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Tournament\n! Level\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2019 Korea Open (badminton)#Finals 2|2019]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Korea Open (badminton)|Korea Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | Super 500\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|THA}} [[Ratchanok Intanon]]\n| align=\"left\" | 18\u201321, 24\u201322, 21\u201317\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2019 India Open (badminton)#Finals 2|2019]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[India Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | Super 500\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|THA}} [[Ratchanok Intanon]]\n| align=\"left\" | 15\u201321, 14\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|-\n| align=\"center\" | [[2018 Malaysia Open (badminton)#Finals 2|2018]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Malaysia Open (badminton)|Malaysia Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | Super 750\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|TPE}} [[Tai Tzu-ying]]\n| align=\"left\" | 20\u201322, 11\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|}\n\n=== BWF Superseries (2 titles, 1 runner-up) ===\nThe BWF Superseries, launched on 14 December 2006 and implemented in 2007, was a series of elite badminton tournaments sanctioned by the [[Badminton World Federation]] (BWF). BWF Superseries had two levels, the [[BWF Superseries|Superseries and Superseries Premier]]. A season of Superseries featured twelve tournaments around the world, introduced in 2011, with successful players invited to the Superseries Finals held at the year's end.\n\n''Women's singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Tournament\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCC\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2017 Japan Super Series#Finals 2|2017]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Japan Open (badminton)|Japan Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|ESP}} [[Carolina Marin]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201323, 12\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCC\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2016 French Super Series#Finals 2|2016]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[French Open (badminton)|French Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|USA}} [[Zhang Beiwen]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u20139, 21\u20139\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#FFFFCC\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2016 Japan Super Series#Finals 2|2016]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Japan Open (badminton)|Japan Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Sun Yu (badminton)|Sun Yu]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201314, 7\u201321, 21\u201318\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|}\n: {{Color box|#B0C4DE|border=darkgray}} [[BWF Superseries Finals]] tournament\n: {{Color box|#DAA520|border=darkgray}} [[BWF Superseries|BWF Superseries Premier]] tournament\n: {{Color box|#FFFFCC|border=darkgray}} [[BWF Superseries]] tournament\n\n=== BWF Grand Prix (5 titles, 2 runners-up) ===\nThe BWF Grand Prix has two levels, the [[BWF Grand Prix and Grand Prix Gold]]. It is a series of badminton tournaments sanctioned by the [[Badminton World Federation]] (BWF) since 2007.\n\n''Women's singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Tournament\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|- style=\"background:#FFFF67\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2016 Bitburger Open Grand Prix Gold#Finals 2|2016]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Bitburger Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|THA}} [[Nitchaon Jindapol]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201311, 21\u201318\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#FFFF67\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2016 Swiss Open Grand Prix Gold#Finals 2|2016]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Swiss Open (badminton)|Swiss Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Wang Yihan]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201316, 21\u201310\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#FFFF67\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2015 Indonesian Masters Grand Prix Gold#Finals 2|2015]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Indonesian Masters (badminton)|Indonesian Masters]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Chen Yufei]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201318, 21\u20139\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#FFFF67\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2015 New Zealand Open Grand Prix Gold#Finals 2|2015]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[New Zealand Open (badminton)|New Zealand Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|JPN}} [[Saena Kawakami]]\n| align=\"left\" | 16\u201321, 18\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#FFFF67\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2015 China Masters Grand Prix Gold#Finals 2|2015]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[China Masters]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Hui Xirui]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201313, 21\u20139\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#FFFF67\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2014 Bitburger Open Grand Prix Gold#Finals 2|2014]]\n| align=\"left\" | Bitburger Open\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Sun Yu (badminton)|Sun Yu]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201316, 15\u201321, 12\u201321\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{silver2}} '''Runner-up'''\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#D4F1C5\"\n| align=\"center\" | [[2013 Vietnam Open Grand Prix#Finals 2|2013]]\n| align=\"left\" | [[Vietnam Open (badminton)|Vietnam Open]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|INA}} [[Hera Desi]]\n| align=\"left\" | 21\u201310, 21\u20136\n| style=\"text-align:left; background:white\" | {{gold1}} '''Winner'''\n|}\n: {{Color box|#FFFF67|border=darkgray}} [[BWF Grand Prix Gold and Grand Prix|BWF Grand Prix Gold]] tournament\n: {{Color box|#D4F1C5|border=darkgray}} [[BWF Grand Prix Gold and Grand Prix|BWF Grand Prix]] tournament\n\n== Record against selected opponents ==\nRecord against year-end Finals finalists, World Championships semi-finalists, and Olympic quarter-finalists. Accurate as of [[2020 All England Open|17 March 2020]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bwf.tournamentsoftware.com/head-2-head?OrganizationCode=209B123F-AA87-41A2-BC3E-CB57133E64CC&T1P1MemberID=87434 |title=He Bingjiao Head to Head |website=bwf.tournamentsoftware.com |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center; font-size:small\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Players\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Matches\n! colspan=\"2\" | Results\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Change\n|-\n! Won\n! 