{"title_page": "Massachusetts Route 3A", "text_new": "{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|type=Route\n|route=3A\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Massachusetts Route 3A}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Route 3A highlighted in red\n|length_mi=97\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"inventory\">[[Executive Office of Transportation (Massachusetts)|Executive Office of Transportation]], [http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content/plan02&sid=about Office of Transportation Planning - 2005 Road Inventory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927193052/http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content%2Fplan02&sid=about |date=2006-09-27 }}</ref>\n|length_round=0\n|established=1926\n|section1=Southern section\n|length_ref1=<ref name=\"inventory\"/>\n|length_mi1=53.392\n|length_round1=3\n|direction_a1=South\n|direction_b1=North\n|terminus_a1={{jct|state=MA|MA|3}} in [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]]\n|junction1={{jct|state=MA|US|44}} in Plymouth<br>{{jct|state=MA|MA|53}} in [[Kingston, Massachusetts|Kingston]]<br>{{jct|state=MA|MA|53}} in [[Quincy, Massachusetts|Quincy]]\n|terminus_b1={{jct|state=MA|I|93|US|1|MA|3|MA|203}} in [[Boston]]\n|section2=Northern section\n|length_mi2=22.5043\n|length_round2=3\n|length_ref2=<ref name=\"inventory\"/>\n|direction_a2=South\n|direction_b2=North\n|terminus_a2={{jct|state=MA|I|95|US|3|MA|128}} in [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]]\n|junction2=[[Lowell Connector]] in [[Lowell, Massachusetts|Lowell]]<br>{{jct|state=MA|MA|110}} in [[Lowell, Massachusetts|Lowell]]<br>{{jct|state=MA|MA|113}} in [[Tyngsborough, Massachusetts|Tyngsborough]]\n|terminus_b2={{jct|state=NH|NH|3A}} in [[Hudson, New Hampshire|Hudson, NH]]\n|counties=[[Plymouth County, Massachusetts|Plymouth]], [[Norfolk County, Massachusetts|Norfolk]], [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk]], [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex]]\n|previous_type=Route\n|previous_route=3\n|next_type=Route\n|next_route=3B\n|browse={{New England browse|previous_type=Route|previous_route=6|route=[[New England Road Marking System|N.E]]|next_type=Route|next_route=7}}\n}}\n'''Route 3A''' is a {{convert|97|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[state highway]] in eastern [[Massachusetts]], which parallels [[Massachusetts Route 3|Route 3]] and [[U.S. Route 3]] from [[Cedarville, Massachusetts|Cedarville]] in southern [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]] to [[Tyngsborough, Massachusetts|Tyngsborough]] at the [[New Hampshire]] state line.\n\nRoute 3A has two major posted segments, separated by a lengthy concurrency with Route 3 and US 3.  Its southern portion parallels [[Route 3 (MA)|Route 3]] from [[Cedarville, Massachusetts|Cedarville]] in southern [[Plymouth (MA)|Plymouth]] to [[Neponset, Massachusetts|Neponset]] in the [[Dorchester, Massachusetts|Dorchester]] area of [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]].  Towns and cities that Route 3A traverse along its path include [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]], [[Kingston, Massachusetts|Kingston]], [[Duxbury, Massachusetts|Duxbury]], [[Marshfield, Massachusetts|Marshfield]], [[Scituate, Massachusetts|Scituate]], [[Cohasset, Massachusetts|Cohasset]], [[Hingham, Massachusetts|Hingham]], [[Weymouth, Massachusetts|Weymouth]] and [[Quincy, Massachusetts|Quincy]].\n\nNorth of Neponset, Route 3A runs, unsigned, concurrently with [[Route 3 (Massachusetts)|Route 3]] and [[U.S. Route 3]] to [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]], before separating again (MassHighway counts the mileage along MA 3 between the two sections as part of MA 3A mileage).\n\nThe northern portion of which parallels [[U.S. Route 3 (MA)|U.S. Route 3]] in northwestern [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex County]]. It stretches from [[Interstate 95 (MA)|Interstate 95]] ([[Route 128 (MA)|Route 128]]) in [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]] to the [[New Hampshire]] state line, where it continues as [[Route 3A (southern New Hampshire)|Route 3A]].\n\n==Route description==\n\n===Plymouth to Boston===\nThis segment parallels [[Massachusetts Route 3|Route 3]] from [[Cedarville, Massachusetts|Cedarville]] in southern [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]] to [[Neponset, Massachusetts|Neponset]] in the [[Dorchester, Boston|Dorchester]] area of [[Boston]].  Towns and cities that Route 3A traverse along its path include [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]], [[Kingston, Massachusetts|Kingston]], [[Duxbury, Massachusetts|Duxbury]], [[Marshfield, Massachusetts|Marshfield]], [[Scituate, Massachusetts|Scituate]], [[Cohasset, Massachusetts|Cohasset]], [[Hingham, Massachusetts|Hingham]], [[Weymouth, Massachusetts|Weymouth]] and [[Quincy, Massachusetts|Quincy]].\n\nThe [[Claire Saltonstall Bikeway]] between Boston and Cape Cod intersects at Route 3A. Once in the Cedarville portion of Plymouth where Route 3A begins, and intersects again about 14 miles later in historic downtown Plymouth between South and Market Streets along Sandwich Street.\n\n===Boston to Burlington===\nThis segment is concurrent with [[Massachusetts Route 3|Route 3]] (to [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]]) and then [[U.S. Route 3]] (from Cambridge to [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]]).  As an 'A' route concurrent with its parents, this segment is not posted.\n\n===Burlington to Tyngsborough===\n[[Image:Northbound MA Route 3A entering Tyngsborough MA.jpg|222px|thumb|right|Northbound 3A entering [[Tyngsborough, Massachusetts|Tyngsborough]]]]\nThis segment parallels [[U.S. Route 3 in Massachusetts|US 3]] from [[Interstate 95 in Massachusetts|Interstate 95]] ([[Massachusetts Route 128|Route 128]]) in [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]] to the [[New Hampshire]] state line, where it continues as [[New Hampshire Route 3A]]. The part south of [[Massachusetts Route 113|Route 113]] in Tyngsborough is former US 3.\n\nThe section from Burlington to Billerica is currently being widened from 2 to 4 lanes.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:New England 6A.svg|50px|left]]\nFrom 1922 to 1926, Route 3A between Kingston and Quincy was [[New England Interstate]] Route 6A. In 1926, when [[New England Interstate Route 6]] became Route 3, Route 6A became Route 3A.\n\nIn the 1930s Route 3A's route was shifted onto new alignments built to reduce traffic problems in several communities through which the highway traversed. This included a bypass of Hingham Square along Broad Cove Road and Otis Street along Hingham Harbor replacing the original route that took it down Lincoln Street to downtown Hingham then along North Street to Summer Street. Chief Justice [[William Cushing|Cushing]] Highway was built around the same time and Route 3A was put on this highway from south of the Hingham Harbor rotary through Cohasset to Scituate. This replaced a routing along long-existing roadways such as Country Way in Scituate, South and North Main Streets in Cohasset and East Street to Summer Street in Hingham. Along East Street from Hull Street to Summer, Route 3A shared the highway with [[Route 128]] in the late 1920s and early 1930s.\n\nIn the 1950s and early 1960s Route 3A was extended to take over the original path of Route 3 south of Kingston to Plymouth and north of downtown Quincy to Neponset when Route 3 assumed its current [[freeway]] route. In between those locations, old Route 3 was designated [[MA Route 53|Route 53]]. The section of old Route 3 from [[Cedarville, Massachusetts|Cedarville]] south to the [[Sagamore Bridge|Sagamore Rotary]] near the [[Cape Cod Canal]] in [[Bourne (MA)|Bourne]] is unnumbered.\n\nMuch of Route 3A is sometimes referred to as the \"Cape Way\" due to its history as the only major road to Cape Cod from Boston prior to the opening of Route 3.  The \"Cape Way\" name is reflected in numerous business names along 3A's length.\n\n[[Image:US 3.svg|45px|right]]The section of Route 3A south of the intersection with [[Route 113 (Massachusetts)|Route 113]] in Tyngsborough (all but the northern few miles of the route) was formerly U.S. Route 3, prior to the construction of the [[Northwest Expressway (Massachusetts)|Northwest Expressway]], a freeway connection from I-95 in Burlington to the [[Everett Turnpike]] in [[Nashua, New Hampshire]], which was given the U.S. Route 3 designation.\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{mileposts}}\n{{jcttop|state=MA|length_ref=}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Plymouth\n|cspan=15\n|location=Plymouth\n|lspan=4\n|mile=0.00\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|3|city1=Boston|city2=Cape Cod}}\n|notes=Southern terminus; Exit 2 on Route 3}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=\n|road=State Road south&nbsp;\u2013 [[Scusset Beach State Reservation|Scusset Beach]]\n|notes=Route 3A joins/leaves State Road}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=11.40\n|road=[[File:MA Route 3.svg|20px]] [[Plimoth Plantation Highway]] to [[Massachusetts Route 3|Route 3]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]], [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]]\n|notes=Southern terminus of Plimouth Plantation Highway}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=15.00\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|44|dir1=west|city1=Middleboro|city2=Taunton}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of US&nbsp;44}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Kingston\n|lspan=4\n|mile=18.30\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|3|city1=Plymouth|city2=Cape Cod|city3=Braintree|city4=Boston}}\n|notes=Exit 9 on Route 3}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=18.70\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|80|dir1=west|US|44|to2=yes}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Route 80}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=18.90\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|106|dir1=west|MA|27|to2=yes|city1=Halifax|city2=Bridgewater}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Route 106}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=20.30\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|53|dir1=north|city1=Hanover}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 53}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Duxbury\n|lspan=3\n|mile=20.60\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|3|city1=Plymouth|city2=Cape Cod|city3=Quincy|city4=Boston}}\n|notes=Exit 10 on Route 3}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=24.20\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|14|dir1=west|city1=Pembroke|city2=Brockton}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Route 14}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=25.00\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|139|city1=Pembroke|city2=Green Harbor}}\n|notes=}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Marshfield\n|lspan=2\n|mile=27.70\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|139|dir1=east|city1=Brant Rock}}\n|notes=Southern end of concurrency with Route 139}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=28.10\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|139|dir1=west|city1=Hanover}}\n|notes=Northern end of concurrency with Route 139}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Scituate\n|mile=34.50\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|123|dir1=west|city1=Norwell|city2=Brockton}}\n|notes=Rotary; Eastern terminus of Route 123}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Hingham\n|mile=42.20\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|228|city1=Hull|city2=Rockland}}\n|notes=}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Norfolk\n|cspan=2\n|location=Quincy\n|lspan=2\n|mile=49.00\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|53|dir1=south|city1=Weymouth}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 53}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=\n|type=incomplete\n|road=Quincy Shore Drive south\n|notes=Interchange; Southbound exit and northbound entrance}}\n{{jctbridge\n|river=[[Neponset River]]\n|mile=\n|bridge=Bridge}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Suffolk\n|cspan=2\n|location=Boston\n|lspan=2\n|mile=53.60\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|203|dir1=west|name1=Gallivan Boulevard|city1=Ashmont|road=Morrisey Boulevard}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Route 203}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=53.61\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|93|US|1|MA|3|dir1=south|dir2=south|dir3=south|city1=Quincy|city2=Cape Cod}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of silent concurrency with Route 3&nbsp;/ US&nbsp;3}}\n{{jctgap|text=See [[Massachusetts Route 3#Exit list|Route 3]]/[[U.S. Route 3#Exit List|US 3]]}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Middlesex\n|cspan=14\n|location=Burlington\n|lspan=3\n|mile=74.8\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|95|US|3|MA|128|city1=Lowell|city2=Burlington|location3=[[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence, RI]]|location4=[[Portsmouth, New Hampshire|Portsmouth, NH]]}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of silent concurrency with Route 3&nbsp;/ US&nbsp;3; Exit 33 on I-95&nbsp;/ Route 128}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=77.20\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|62|dir1=east|city1=Wilmington|city2=North Reading}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of concurrency with Route 62}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=77.80\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|62|dir1=west|city1=Bedford|city2=Concord}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of concurrency with Route 62}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Billerica\n|lspan=2\n|mile=82.40\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|129|dir1=east|city1=Reading|city2=Wakefield}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of concurrency with Route 129}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=83.60\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|129|dir1=west|city1=Chelmsford|location2=[[Nashua, New Hampshire|Nashua, NH]]|US|3|to2=yes}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of concurrency with Route 129}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Lowell\n|lspan=3\n|mile=87.30\n|road=[[File:I-495.svg|25px]][[File:US 3.svg|20px]] [[Lowell Connector]] south to [[Interstate 495 (Massachusetts)|I-495]]&nbsp;/ [[U.S. Route 3 in Massachusetts|US&nbsp;3]]\n|notes=Exits 5A-B on the Lowell Connector}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=87.70\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|110|dir1=east|city1=Haverhill|city2=Lawrence|road=Thorndike Street}}\n|notes=Partial interchange; Southern terminus of concurrency with Route 110}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=87.90\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|110|dir1=west|city1=Chelmsford|city2=Littleton}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of concurrency with Route 110|}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Chelmsford\n|lspan=2\n|mile=91.10\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|4|dir1=south|US|3|to2=yes|city1=Chelmsford|city2=Lexington}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 4}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=91.80\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|40|dir1=west|city1=Westford|city2=Groton}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Route 40}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Tyngsborough\n|lspan=4\n|mile=95.10\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|113|dir1=west|city1=Dunstable}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of concurrency with Route 113}}\n{{jctbridge\n|mile=\n|bridge=Tyngsborough Bridge over the [[Merrimack River]]}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=95.30\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|113|dir1=east|city1=Lowell}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of concurrency with Route 113}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=97.00\n|road={{jct|state=NH|NH|3A|dir1=north|city1=Hudson}}\n|notes=Continuation into [[New Hampshire]]}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur,incomplete}}\n\n==References==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{Commons category|Massachusetts Route 3A}}\n\n[[Category:Numbered routes in Massachusetts|003A]]\n[[Category:Plymouth, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Kingston, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Duxbury, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Marshfield, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Scituate, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Cohasset, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Hingham, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Weymouth, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Quincy, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Boston]]\n[[Category:Burlington, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Billerica, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Chelmsford, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Lowell, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Tyngsborough, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Plymouth County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Norfolk County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Suffolk County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 3]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox road\n|state=MA\n|type=Route\n|route=3A\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=290|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Massachusetts Route 3A}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=Route 3A highlighted in red\n|length_mi=97\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"inventory\">[[Executive Office of Transportation (Massachusetts)|Executive Office of Transportation]], [http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content/plan02&sid=about Office of Transportation Planning - 2005 Road Inventory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927193052/http://www.eot.state.ma.us/default.asp?pgid=content%2Fplan02&sid=about |date=2006-09-27 }}</ref>\n|length_round=0\n|established=1926\n|section1=Southern section\n|length_ref1=<ref name=\"inventory\"/>\n|length_mi1=53.392\n|length_round1=3\n|direction_a1=South\n|direction_b1=North\n|terminus_a1={{jct|state=MA|MA|3}} in [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]]\n|junction1={{jct|state=MA|US|44}} in Plymouth<br>{{jct|state=MA|MA|53}} in [[Kingston, Massachusetts|Kingston]]<br>{{jct|state=MA|MA|53}} in [[Quincy, Massachusetts|Quincy]]\n|terminus_b1={{jct|state=MA|I|93|US|1|MA|3|MA|203}} in [[Boston]]\n|section2=Northern section\n|length_mi2=22.5043\n|length_round2=3\n|length_ref2=<ref name=\"inventory\"/>\n|direction_a2=South\n|direction_b2=North\n|terminus_a2={{jct|state=MA|I|95|US|3|MA|128}} in [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]]\n|junction2=[[Lowell Connector]] in [[Lowell, Massachusetts|Lowell]]<br>{{jct|state=MA|MA|110}} in [[Lowell, Massachusetts|Lowell]]<br>{{jct|state=MA|MA|113}} in [[Tyngsborough, Massachusetts|Tyngsborough]]\n|terminus_b2={{jct|state=NH|NH|3A}} in [[Hudson, New Hampshire|Hudson, NH]]\n|counties=[[Plymouth County, Massachusetts|Plymouth]], [[Norfolk County, Massachusetts|Norfolk]], [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk]], [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex]]\n|previous_type=Route\n|previous_route=3\n|next_type=Route\n|next_route=3B\n|browse={{New England browse|previous_type=Route|previous_route=6|route=[[New England Road Marking System|N.E]]|next_type=Route|next_route=7}}\n}}\n'''Route 3A''' is a {{convert|97|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[state highway]] in eastern [[Massachusetts]], which parallels [[Massachusetts Route 3|Route 3]] and [[U.S. Route 3]] from [[Cedarville, Massachusetts|Cedarville]] in southern [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]] to [[Tyngsborough, Massachusetts|Tyngsborough]] at the [[New Hampshire]] state line.\n\nRoute 3A has two major posted segments, separated by a lengthy concurrency with Route 3 and US 3.  Its southern portion parallels [[Route 3 (MA)|Route 3]] from [[Cedarville, Massachusetts|Cedarville]] in southern [[Plymouth (MA)|Plymouth]] to [[Neponset, Massachusetts|Neponset]] in the [[Dorchester, Massachusetts|Dorchester]] area of [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]].  Towns and cities that Route 3A traverse along its path include [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]], [[Kingston, Massachusetts|Kingston]], [[Duxbury, Massachusetts|Duxbury]], [[Marshfield, Massachusetts|Marshfield]], [[Scituate, Massachusetts|Scituate]], [[Cohasset, Massachusetts|Cohasset]], [[Hingham, Massachusetts|Hingham]], [[Weymouth, Massachusetts|Weymouth]] and [[Quincy, Massachusetts|Quincy]].\n\nNorth of Neponset, Route 3A runs, unsigned, concurrently with [[Route 3 (Massachusetts)|Route 3]] and [[U.S. Route 3]] to [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]], before separating again (MassHighway counts the mileage along MA 3 between the two sections as part of MA 3A mileage).\n\nThe northern portion of which parallels [[U.S. Route 3 (MA)|U.S. Route 3]] in northwestern [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex County]]. It stretches from [[Interstate 95 (MA)|Interstate 95]] ([[Route 128 (MA)|Route 128]]) in [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]] to the [[New Hampshire]] state line, where it continues as [[Route 3A (southern New Hampshire)|Route 3A]].\n\n==Route description==\n\n===Plymouth to Boston===\nThis segment parallels [[Massachusetts Route 3|Route 3]] from [[Cedarville, Massachusetts|Cedarville]] in southern [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]] to [[Neponset, Massachusetts|Neponset]] in the [[Dorchester, Boston|Dorchester]] area of [[Boston]].  Towns and cities that Route 3A traverse along its path include [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]], [[Kingston, Massachusetts|Kingston]], [[Duxbury, Massachusetts|Duxbury]], [[Marshfield, Massachusetts|Marshfield]], [[Scituate, Massachusetts|Scituate]], [[Cohasset, Massachusetts|Cohasset]], [[Hingham, Massachusetts|Hingham]], [[Weymouth, Massachusetts|Weymouth]] and [[Quincy, Massachusetts|Quincy]].\n\nThe [[Claire Saltonstall Bikeway]] between Boston and Cape Cod intersects at Route 3A. Once in the Cedarville portion of Plymouth where Route 3A begins, and intersects again about 14 miles later in historic downtown Plymouth between South and Market Streets along Sandwich Street.\n\n===Boston to Burlington===\nThis segment is concurrent with [[Massachusetts Route 3|Route 3]] (to [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]]) and then [[U.S. Route 3]] (from Cambridge to [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]]).  As an 'A' route concurrent with its parents, this segment is not posted.\n\n===Burlington to Tyngsborough===\n[[Image:Northbound MA Route 3A entering Tyngsborough MA.jpg|222px|thumb|right|Northbound 3A entering [[Tyngsborough, Massachusetts|Tyngsborough]]]]\nThis segment parallels [[U.S. Route 3 in Massachusetts|US 3]] from [[Interstate 95 in Massachusetts|Interstate 95]] ([[Massachusetts Route 128|Route 128]]) in [[Burlington, Massachusetts|Burlington]] to the [[New Hampshire]] state line, where it continues as [[New Hampshire Route 3A]]. The part south of [[Massachusetts Route 113|Route 113]] in Tyngsborough is former US 3.\n\nThe section from Burlington to Billerica is currently being widened from 2 to 4 lanes.\n\n==History==\n[[Image:New England 6A.svg|50px|left]]\nFrom 1922 to 1926, Route 3A between Kingston and Quincy was [[New England Interstate]] Route 6A. In 1926, when [[New England Interstate Route 6]] became Route 3, Route 6A became Route 3A.\n\nIn the 1930s Route 3A's route was shifted onto new alignments built to reduce traffic problems in several communities through which the highway traversed. This included a bypass of Hingham Square along Broad Cove Road and Otis Street along Hingham Harbor replacing the original route that took it down Lincoln Street to downtown Hingham then along North Street to Summer Street. Chief Justice [[William Cushing|Cushing]] Highway was built around the same time and Route 3A was put on this highway from south of the Hingham Harbor rotary through Cohasset to Scituate. This replaced a routing along long-existing roadways such as Country Way in Scituate, South and North Main Streets in Cohasset and East Street to Summer Street in Hingham. Along East Street from Hull Street to Summer, Route 3A shared the highway with [[Route 128]] in the late 1920s and early 1930s.\n\nIn the 1950s and early 1960s Route 3A was extended to take over the original path of Route 3 south of Kingston to Plymouth and north of downtown Quincy to Neponset when Route 3 assumed its current [[freeway]] route. In between those locations, old Route 3 was designated [[MA Route 53|Route 53]]. The section of old Route 3 from [[Cedarville, Massachusetts|Cedarville]] south to the [[Sagamore Bridge|Sagamore Rotary]] near the [[Cape Cod Canal]] in [[Bourne (MA)|Bourne]] is unnumbered.\n\nMuch of Route 3A is sometimes referred to as the \"Cape Way\" due to its history as the only major road to Cape Cod from Boston prior to the opening of Route 3.  The \"Cape Way\" name is reflected in numerous business names along 3A's length.\n\n[[Image:US 3.svg|45px|right]]The section of Route 3A south of the intersection with [[Route 113 (Massachusetts)|Route 113]] in Tyngsborough (all but the northern few miles of the route) was formerly U.S. Route 3, prior to the construction of the [[Northwest Expressway (Massachusetts)|Northwest Expressway]], a freeway connection from I-95 in Burlington to the [[Everett Turnpike]] in [[Nashua, New Hampshire]], which was given the U.S. Route 3 designation.\n\n==Major intersections==\n{{mileposts}}\n{{jcttop|state=MA|length_ref=}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Plymouth\n|cspan=15\n|location=Plymouth\n|lspan=4\n|mile=0.00\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|3|location1=[[Boston]]|location2=[[Cape Cod]]}}\n|notes=Southern terminus; Exit 2 on Route 3}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=\n|road=State Road south&nbsp;\u2013 [[Scusset Beach State Reservation|Scusset Beach]]\n|notes=Route 3A joins/leaves State Road}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=11.40\n|road=[[File:MA Route 3.svg|20px]] [[Plimoth Plantation Highway]] to [[Massachusetts Route 3|Route 3]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Plymouth, Massachusetts|Plymouth]], [[Boston]]\n|notes=Southern terminus of Plimouth Plantation Highway}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=15.00\n|road={{jct|state=MA|US|44|dir1=west|city1=Middleborough|location2=[[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]]}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of US&nbsp;44}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Kingston\n|lspan=4\n|mile=18.30\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|3|city1=Plymouth|location2=[[Cape Cod]]|city3=Braintree|location4=[[Boston]]}}\n|notes=Exit 9 on Route 3}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=18.70\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|80|dir1=west|US|44|to2=yes}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Route 80}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=18.90\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|106|dir1=west|MA|27|to2=yes|city1=Halifax}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Route 106}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=20.30\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|53|dir1=north|city1=Hanover}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of Route 53}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Duxbury\n|lspan=3\n|mile=20.60\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|3|city1=Plymouth|location2=[[Cape Cod]]|city3=Quincy|location4=[[Boston]]}}\n|notes=Exit 10 on Route 3}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=24.20\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|14|dir1=west|city1=Pembroke|location2=[[Boston]]}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Route 14}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=25.00\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|139|city1=Pembroke|city2=Green Harbor}}\n|notes=}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Marshfield\n|lspan=2\n|mile=27.70\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|139|dir1=east|city1=Brant Rock}}\n|notes=Southern end of concurrency with Route 139}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=28.10\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|139|dir1=west|city1=Hanover}}\n|notes=Northern end of concurrency with Route 139}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Scituate\n|mile=34.50\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|123|dir1=west|city1=Norwell|city2=Brockton}}\n|notes=Rotary; Eastern terminus of Route 123}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Hingham\n|mile=42.20\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|228|city1=Hull|city2=Rockland}}\n|notes=}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Norfolk\n|cspan=2\n|location=Quincy\n|lspan=2\n|mile=49.00\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|53|dir1=south|city1=Weymouth}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 53}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=\n|type=incomplete\n|road=Quincy Shore Drive south\n|notes=Interchange; Southbound exit and northbound entrance}}\n{{jctbridge\n|river=[[Neponset River]]\n|mile=\n|bridge=Bridge}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Suffolk\n|cspan=2\n|location=Boston\n|lspan=2\n|mile=53.60\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|203|dir1=west|name1=Gallivan Boulevard|city1=Ashmont|road=Morrisey Boulevard}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Route 203}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=53.61\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|93|US|1|MA|3|dir1=south|dir2=south|dir3=south}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of silent concurrency with Route 3&nbsp;/ US&nbsp;3}}\n{{jctgap|text=See [[Massachusetts Route 3#Exit list|Route 3]]/[[U.S. Route 3#Exit List|US 3]]}}\n{{MAint\n|county=Middlesex\n|cspan=14\n|location=Burlington\n|lspan=3\n|mile=74.8\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|I|95|US|3|MA|128|city1=Waltham|city2=Lowell|city3=Peabody|location4=[[Portsmouth, New Hampshire|Portsmouth, NH]]}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of silent concurrency with Route 3&nbsp;/ US&nbsp;3; Exit 33 on I-95&nbsp;/ Route 128}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=77.20\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|62|dir1=east|city1=Wilmington|city2=North Reading}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of concurrency with Route 62}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=77.80\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|62|dir1=west|city1=Bedford|city2=Concord}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of concurrency with Route 62}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Billerica\n|lspan=2\n|mile=82.40\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|129|dir1=east|city1=Reading|city2=Wakefield}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of concurrency with Route 129}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=83.60\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|129|dir1=west|city1=Chelmsford|location2=[[Nashua, New Hampshire|Nashua, NH]]|US|3|to2=yes}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of concurrency with Route 129}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Lowell\n|lspan=3\n|mile=87.30\n|road=[[File:I-495.svg|25px]][[File:US 3.svg|20px]] [[Lowell Connector]] south to [[Interstate 495 (Massachusetts)|I-495]]&nbsp;/ [[U.S. Route 3 in Massachusetts|US&nbsp;3]]\n|notes=Exits 5A-B on the Lowell Connector}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=87.70\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|110|dir1=east|city1=Haverhill|city2=Lawrence|road=Thorndike Street}}\n|notes=Partial interchange; Southern terminus of concurrency with Route 110}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=87.90\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|110|dir1=west|city1=Chelmsford|city2=Worcester}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of concurrency with Route 110|}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Chelmsford\n|lspan=2\n|mile=91.10\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|4|dir1=south|US|3|to2=yes|city1=Chelmsford|city2=Lexington}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of Route 4}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=91.80\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|40|dir1=west|city1=Groton}}\n|notes=Eastern terminus of Route 40}}\n{{MAint\n|location=Tyngsborough\n|lspan=4\n|mile=95.10\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|113|dir1=west|city1=Dunstable}}\n|notes=Southern terminus of concurrency with Route 113}}\n{{jctbridge\n|mile=\n|bridge=Tyngsborough Bridge over the [[Merrimack River]]}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=95.30\n|type=concur\n|road={{jct|state=MA|MA|113|dir1=east|city1=Lowell}}\n|notes=Northern terminus of concurrency with Route 113}}\n{{MAint\n|mile=97.00\n|road={{jct|state=NH|NH|3A|dir1=north|city1=Hudson}}\n|notes=Continuation into [[New Hampshire]]}}\n{{jctbtm|keys=concur,incomplete}}\n\n==References==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n{{reflist}}\n{{Commons category|Massachusetts Route 3A}}\n\n[[Category:Numbered routes in Massachusetts|003A]]\n[[Category:Plymouth, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Kingston, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Duxbury, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Marshfield, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Scituate, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Cohasset, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Hingham, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Weymouth, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Quincy, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Boston]]\n[[Category:Burlington, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Billerica, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Chelmsford, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Lowell, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Tyngsborough, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Plymouth County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Norfolk County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Suffolk County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:U.S. Route 3]]\n", "name_user": "Oliver Wendell 2009", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMajor intersections", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Massachusetts_Route_3A"}
{"title_page": "George Nicholson (diplomat)", "text_new": "{{short description|Former English diplomat in Scotland}}\n'''George Nicholson''' or '''Nicolson''' (floruit 1577-1612), was an English diplomat in Scotland.\n\n==Resident in Scotland==\nGeorge Nicholson was not an ambassador in Scotland but a resident agent. He had been a servant of [[Robert Bowes (diplomat)|Robert Bowes]] for many years. Bowes became unwell in 1597 and intended Nicholson should take his place. On 6 December 1597 [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth]] wrote to [[James VI of Scotland |James VI]] accrediting to be resident in Scotland. Nicholson was to get 13s-4d per day and the Governor of [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]]. Nicholson was soon treated and functioned as ambassador in all but name. Most of his letters were sent to the [[Secretary of State (England)|Secretary]], [[Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Sir Robert Cecil]].<ref>J. D. Mackie, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1597-1603'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), pp. xxi-xii, 126.</ref>\n\nHis network of contacts at the Scottish court built on the organisation made by [[Bowes]] and the English courtier [[Roger Aston]], and he came treat James VI in a familar way. Cecil from time to time reminded him of his low status as an agent, rather than an ambassador who were usually drawn from the aristocracy. He may have been insensitive, or lacked some tact, he came to the king at [[Dunfermline]] seeking an audience while the court was in mourning for [[Robert Stuart, Duke of Kintyre and Lorne|Duke Robert]] and the [[Treasurer of Scotland]], [[George Home, 1st Earl of Dunbar|Sir George Home]] sent him away.<ref>J. D. Mackie, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1597-1603'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), pp. xxii-xxvii, 999.</ref>\n\n==Scottish affairs==\nIn August 1595 Nicholson rode to [[Loch Lomond]] and the castle on [[Inchmurrin]] with Elizabeth's letters for James VI, where the king often went on annual hunting trips. Sir George Home told him to note that the king received [[Lachlan Mor Maclean]] to his favour. MacLean and the [[Archibald Campbell, 7th Earl of Argyll|Earl of Argyll]] went hunting with the king at a \"mean house\" belonging to Argyll.<ref>M. S. Giuseppi, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1595-1597'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1952), pp. 3-4.</ref> In September he went to [[Falkland Palace]] where he observed at first hand the feud between between [[Anne of Denmark]] and the [[Earl of Mar]], who was the keeper of her son, [[Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]]. The queen would not look to that side of the chamber where the Earl stood. She said she would not go to [[Stirling]] for fear they would give her a poisoned [[posset]], despite the king's wish that she would go with him to [[Linlithgow Palace|Linlithow]] and then to [[Stirling Castle]], where Mar and his mother [[Annabell Murray, Countess of Mar|Annabell Murray]] kept Prince Henry.<ref>M. S. Giuseppi, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1952), p. 18.</ref>  \n\nOn 16 January 1598 he reported on the illness of the bankrupt financier [[Thomas Foulis]] who \"fell madd sick this day\" either because of his debts, or because James VI had taken a valuable jewel from him, known as the \"[[Great H of Scotland]].\" The jewel had been pawned by the king to finance his campaigns against the Catholic northern earls. Nicholson says that [[Anne of Denmark]] gave the jewel to her friend, the [[Elizabeth Douglas, Countess of Erroll|Countess of Erroll]], as a joke, saying that it was little enough for her to have it for a night for the casting down of her husband's house, [[Old Slains Castle]].<ref>Joseph Bain, [https://archive.org/details/borderpaperscale02grea/page/504/mode/2up/ ''Calendar of Border Papers'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1894), p. 504.]</ref>\n\nNicholson could not speak French so when he met the French ambassador in 1602, the [[Charles Cauchon de Maupas|Baron de Tour]], the [[Robert Crichton, 8th Lord Crichton of Sanquhar|Lord Sanquhar]] acted as interpreter for him.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 1033-4.</ref>\n\nIn October 1602 he was in Berwick discussing the border Graham family with [[Thomas Scrope, 10th Baron Scrope of Bolton|Thomas Scrope]], the [[Lord Warden of the Marches|Warden of the West March]], and helped the Grahams prepare a petition.<ref>Joseph Bain, [https://archive.org/details/borderpaperscale02grea/page/806/mode/2up ''Calendar of Border Papers'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1894), p. 806.]</ref> \n\n==Retirement==\nIn August 1603, after the [[Union of the Crowns]], Nicholson was given an allowance of 5s-6d. per day.<ref>''HMC Cecil Hatfield'', vol. 11, p. 23.</ref> He seems to have then worked at Berwick, as Paymaster, and sent accounts of the garrison to the auditor, [[Francis Gofton]] in 1612.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, James I: 1611-1618'' (London, 1858), p. 112.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nicholson, George}}\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of England to Scotland]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:16th-century English diplomats]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Former English diplomat in Scotland}}\n'''George Nicholson''' or '''Nicolson''' (floruit 1577-1612), was an English diplomat in Scotland.\n\n==Resident in Scotland==\nGeorge Nicholson was not an ambassador in Scotland but a resident agent. He had been a servant of [[Robert Bowes (diplomat)|Robert Bowes]] for many years. Bowes became unwell in 1597 and intended Nicholson should take his place. On 6 December 1597 [[Elizabeth I of England|Queen Elizabeth]] wrote to [[James VI of Scotland |James VI]] accrediting to be resident in Scotland. Nicholson was to get 13s-4d per day and the Governor of [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]]. Nicholson was soon treated and functioned as ambassador in all but name. Most of his letters were sent to the [[Secretary of State (England)|Secretary]], [[Robert Cecil, 1st Earl of Salisbury|Sir Robert Cecil]].<ref>J. D. Mackie, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1597-1603'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), pp. xxi-xii, 126.</ref>\n\nHis network of contacts at the Scottish court built on the organisation made by [[Bowes]] and the English courtier [[Roger Aston]], and he came treat James VI in a familar way. Cecil from time to time reminded him of his low status as an agent, rather than an ambassador who were usually drawn from the aristocracy. He may have been insensitive, or lacked some tact, he came to the king at [[Dunfermline]] seeking an audience while the court was in mourning for [[Robert Stuart, Duke of Kintyre and Lorne|Duke Robert]] and the [[Treasurer of Scotland]], [[George Home, 1st Earl of Dunbar|Sir George Home]] sent him away.<ref>J. D. Mackie, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1597-1603'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), pp. xxii-xxvii, 999.</ref>\n\n==Scottish affairs==\nIn August 1595 Nicholson rode to [[Loch Lomond]] and the castle on [[Inchmurrin]] with Elizabeth's letters for James VI, where the king often went on annual hunting trips. Sir George Home told him to note that the king received [[Lachlan Mor Maclean]] to his favour. MacLean and the [[Archibald Campbell, 7th Earl of Argyll|Earl of Argyll]] went hunting with the king at a \"mean house\" belonging to Argyll.<ref>M. S. Giuseppi, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland: 1595-1597'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1952), pp. 3-4.</ref> In September he went to [[Falkland Palace]] where he observed at first hand the feud between between [[Anne of Denmark]] and the [[Earl of Mar]], who was the keeper of her son, [[Henry Frederick, Prince of Wales|Prince Henry]]. The queen would not look to that side of the chamber where the Earl stood. She said she would not go to [[Stirling]] for fear they would give her a poisoned [[posset]], despite the king's wish that she would go with him to [[Linlithgow Palace|Linlithow]] and then to [[Stirling Castle]], where Mar and his mother [[Annabell Murray, Countess of Mar|Annabell Murray]] kept Prince Henry.<ref>M. S. Giuseppi, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1952), pp. 3-4.</ref>  \n\nOn 16 January 1598 he reported on the illness of the bankrupt financier [[Thomas Foulis]] who \"fell madd sick this day\" either because of his debts, or because James VI had taken a valuable jewel from him, known as the \"[[Great H of Scotland]].\" The jewel had been pawned by the king to finance his campaigns against the Catholic northern earls. Nicholson says that [[Anne of Denmark]] gave the jewel to her friend, the [[Elizabeth Douglas, Countess of Erroll|Countess of Erroll]], as a joke, saying that it was little enough for her to have it for a night for the casting down of her husband's house, [[Old Slains Castle]].<ref>Joseph Bain, [https://archive.org/details/borderpaperscale02grea/page/504/mode/2up/ ''Calendar of Border Papers'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1894), p. 504.]</ref>\n\nNicholson could not speak French so when he met the French ambassador in 1602, the [[Charles Cauchon de Maupas|Baron de Tour]], the [[Robert Crichton, 8th Lord Crichton of Sanquhar|Lord Sanquhar]] acted as interpreter for him.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 1033-4.</ref>\n\nIn October 1602 he was in Berwick discussing the border Graham family with [[Thomas Scrope, 10th Baron Scrope of Bolton|Thomas Scrope]], the [[Lord Warden of the Marches|Warden of the West March]], and helped the Grahams prepare a petition.<ref>Joseph Bain, [https://archive.org/details/borderpaperscale02grea/page/806/mode/2up ''Calendar of Border Papers'', vol. 2 (Edinburgh, 1894), p. 806.]</ref> \n\n==Retirement==\nIn August 1603, after the [[Union of the Crowns]], Nicholson was given an allowance of 5s-6d. per day.<ref>''HMC Cecil Hatfield'', vol. 11, p. 23.</ref> He seems to have then worked at Berwick, as Paymaster, and sent accounts of the garrison to the auditor, [[Francis Gofton]] in 1612.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Domestic, James I: 1611-1618'' (London, 1858), p. 112.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nicholson, George}}\n[[Category:Court of James VI and I]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of England to Scotland]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:16th-century English diplomats]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Nicholson_(diplomat)"}
